description: Data was loaded from the GENCODE reference gene set, release 22, dated March 2015. These annotations are based on the hg38/GRCh38 reference genome. More details: Harrow J, et al. (2012) GENCODE: The reference human genome annotation for The ENCODE Project http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/22955987 and ftp://ftp.sanger.ac.uk/pub/gencode/Gencode_human/release_22/gencode.v22.annotation.gtf.gz

fields.description: E.g., an exon, CDS, UTR, transcript, etc.
fields.name: feature

fields.description: + or -, for forward or reverse strand. DNA is double-stranded. By convention, for a reference chromosome, one whole strand is designated the forward strand and the other the reverse strand. This designation is arbitrary. Sometimes the terms plus strand and minus strand are used instead.
fields.name: strand

fields.description: Ensembl gene ID. Stable IDs are created in the form ENS[species prefix][feature type prefix][a unique eleven digit number]. For example, a mouse gene might be ENSMUSG###########. For human, there is no species code, so IDs are in the form ENS(object type)(identifier).(version). E.g., ENSG00000183091. See https://useast.ensembl.org/Help/Faq?id=488
fields.name: gene_id

fields.description: Ensembl gene ID with version. E.g.,ENSG00000155657.22
fields.name: gene_id_v

fields.description: E.g., TTN-018 (corresponding to Ensembl transcript ID ENST00000589042.1 in GRCh37p.13)
fields.name: transcript_name

fields.description: Ensembl transcript ID. Stable IDs are created in the form ENS[species prefix][feature type prefix][a unique eleven digit number].For human, there is no species code, so IDs are in the form ENS(object type)(identifier).(version) E.g, ENT00000589042.
fields.name: transcript_id

fields.description: E.g., protein_coding, nonsense_mediated_decay, processed_transcript, retained_intron, lincRNA, antisense, etc.
fields.name: transcript_type

fields.description: A number between 1 and 5. The Transcript Support Level (TSL) is a method to highlight the well-supported and poorly-supported transcript models for users. The method relies on the primary data that can support full-length transcript structure: mRNA and EST alignments supplied by UCSC and Ensembl.The mRNA and EST alignments are compared to the GENCODE transcripts and the transcripts are scored according to how well the alignment matches over its full length. The GENCODE TSL provides a consistent method of evaluating the level of support that a GENCODE transcript annotation is actually expressed in humans. See https://useast.ensembl.org/info/genome/genebuild/transcript_quality_tags.html
fields.name: transcript_support_level

fields.description: Position number in set of of exons for parent gene. See https://useast.ensembl.org/info/genome/genebuild/genome_annotation.html
fields.name: exon_number

fields.description: Ensembl exon ID. Stable IDs are created in the form ENS[species prefix][feature type prefix][a unique eleven digit number].For human, there is no species code, so IDs are in the form ENS(object type)(identifier).(version).E.g, ENSE00003674202
fields.name: exon_id

fields.description: E.g., CCDS54408 The CCDS project is a collaborative effort to identify a core set ofprotein coding regions that are consistently annotated and of high quality. The CCDS set is built by consensus among Ensembl, the National Center for Biotechnology Information (NCBI), and the HUGO Gene Nomenclature Committee (HGNC) for human or Mouse Genome Informatics (MGI) for mouse. Annotated genes that are included in the CCDS set are associated with a unique identifier number and version number (e.g., CCDS1.1, CCDS234.1). The version number will update if the CDS structure changes, or if the underlying genome sequence changes at that location. See https://useast.ensembl.org/info/genome/genebuild/ccds.html
fields.name: ccds_id

fields.description: E.g., CCDS54408.1 The CCDS project is a collaborative effort to identify a core set ofprotein coding regions that are consistently annotated and of high quality. Annotated genes that are included in the CCDS set are associated with a unique identifier number and version number (e.g., CCDS1.1, CCDS234.1). The version number will update if the CDS structure changes, or if the underlying genome sequence changes at that location. See https://useast.ensembl.org/info/genome/genebuild/ccds.html
